<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Pooly</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I can't believe I haven't heard about this from other FreeBSD users...<P>FreeBSD had some changes made to the threading system since 4.2-RELEASE which basically slow down ShowEQ significantly. It seems as if updates get paused for 10-20 seconds, and then it updates. It keeps going like this. So basically, ShowEQ doesn't show what's happening, it shows what happened 10-20 seconds ago.<P>I tried playing with nice values, setting real-time priority (using the rtprio program and ShowEQ's option to set the network thread to realtime priority), but they have no effect (other than to perhaps slow down the rest of the system). Top shows ShowEQ going idle for that 10-20 second period where it does nothing. The menus and stuff react instantly, but updates of EQ do not. If I con something, it also waits for that 10-20 second period to be over before it highlights it on the spawnlist.<P>As I said, it works fine on 4.2-RELEASE (updates are constant and nearly instantaneous), but it's slow even with a cvsup of today's -STABLE sources. It makes no difference if I'm running this on a Pentium-133 or an Athlon 750. In fact, the Pentium-133 running FreeBSD 4.2-R runs ShowEQ better than the Athlon-750 running the latest 4.2-STABLE.<P>I was wondering if anyone had any ideas on how to fix this. I don't know anything about programming with thread support, but.. perhaps there's some place in the ShowEQ source where thread priority can be changed?<P>I suppose I could switch to -CURRENT if I need to, but that's kind of a last resort.<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Step</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Oh.. dont tell me that.. just took off Redhat to put on FreeBSD 4.2 Release. Havent taken the time out yet to install ShowEQ yet, but if its as bad as you say I dont think ill bother =(</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Pooly</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">It runs just fine on 4.2-RELEASE. Just don't cvsup and make world.<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">casey</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">&gt; I can't believe I haven't heard about this from other FreeBSD users...<P>I've heard it from at least 3 people in the #showeq irc channel, i've been referring them to you though for help since most everone who idles there are linux users </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Pooly</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">This weekend, I've had another chance to observe SEQ on a post 4.2-R system. I noticed that the gui updates were still happening (map updates were occurring normally but mob position followed the prediction vectors, scrollbar reaction was instant). It just wasn't reacting to captured packets instantly.<P>Anyways, is there a developer I could get in touch with who could make any sense of this? I have 2 systems, one with 4.2-R and one with a more recent FreeBSD, which I could run whatever debugging tools on, etc. to get the info needed to track the problem down.<BR><p>[This message has been edited by Pooly (edited 04-15-2001).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Geng</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I've been having the same update problems in FreeBSD 4.2 and 4.3, using SEQ 2.5x.  I hoped it would go away with the v3x update, but after getting it installed and running today from CVS it looks like it's still there for me. <P>This all used to work and I'm not sure exactly when it stopped updating correctly, but I haven't been able to get it working again properly on new clean installs.<P>If anyone has any suggestions, I'm sure there's many of us out there who are stumped.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">ignotus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Threading code in FreeBSD changed somewhere between 4.1-RELEASE and 4.2-STABLE. <P>Since I got a spare FreeBSD system that does nothing but be my TV, my browser and my ShowEQ monitor, I just downgraded back to 4.1-REALEASE. Works perfect now, isntant updates.<P>It might be solved with 5-RELEASE or something... no clue where they are going with the thread-code in FreeBSD.<BR></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
